  "reason_thou": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe crash is an assertion failure,
`!isInvalid() && \"Loop not in a valid state!\"`, which occurs when `getSubLoops()` is called
on a `Loop` object that has been invalidated. A `Loop` object becomes invalid when the
underlying loop structure it represents is deleted or significantly altered (e.g., by
unrolling it completely). The backtrace shows this happens within the `loop-unroll-and-jam`
pass, specifically when it's trying to add sub-loops of a processed loop to a worklist for
further processing.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log provides crucial
clues:\n- **ScalarEvolution Analysis**: It correctly deduces that the middle loop
(`%do.body2`) has a trip count of 1 (since its backedge is never taken, it executes once).\n-
**LoopUnrollAndJam Pass**:\n    - It first considers the innermost loop (`%while.cond3`) and
correctly skips it as ineligible.\n    - It then processes the middle loop (`%do.body2`).
Seeing the trip count is 1, it decides to \"COMPLETELY UNROLL AND JAMMING\" it. This is the
key transformation. Completely unrolling a loop effectively removes it from the loop
hierarchy.\n    - The crash happens after this unrolling, when the pass proceeds to handle
other loops.\n\nThe sequence of events is:\n1. The pass gets a list of all loops in the
function.\n2. It processes the middle loop and completely unrolls it. This action *deletes*
the middle loop and invalidates its corresponding `Loop*` pointer.\n3. The pass continues its
work, and later tries to access the sub-loops of the now-deleted middle loop, leading to the
assertion failure.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe core of the problem lies in how
`LoopUnrollAndJamPass` iterates over loops and how it handles the side effects of its own
transformations.\n\nThe pass receives a `LoopNest` object, which contains a list of loops to
process. The `tryToUnrollAndJamLoop` function iterates through these loops. When it completely
unrolls the middle loop (`%do.body2`), the `Loop` object for it is destroyed. However, the
`LoopNest`'s list of loops is not updated to reflect this deletion.\n\nLater, in
`tryToUnrollAndJamLoop`, the code calls `appendLoopsToWorklist` on the `LoopNest`'s original
list of loops. This function iterates through the loops and, for each one, tries to add its
sub-loops to a worklist. When it reaches the pointer to the now-deleted middle loop, it calls
`getSubLoops()` on an invalid `Loop` object, triggering the crash.\n\nThe fix is to ensure
that after a loop is completely unrolled and deleted, we do not attempt to process it or its
(non-existent) sub-loops further. A simple way to achieve this is to skip any invalid loops
when populating the worklist for the next stage of the pass.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit
Point(s)\n\nThe issue can be resolved by adding a check in `appendReversedLoopsToWorklist` to
ensure we don't process loops that have been invalidated.\n\n**File**:
`llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopUtils.cpp`\n\n```cpp\n---
a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopUtils.cpp\n+++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopUtils.cpp\n@@
-1803,6 +1803,8 @@\n template <typename R>\n void appendReversedLoopsToWorklist(R &&Loops,\n
SmallPriorityWorklist<Loop *, 4> &Worklist) {\n   for (Loop *L : Loops)\n     for (Loop *SubL
: llvm::reverse(L->getSubLoops()))\n       Worklist.push(SubL);\n }\n```\n\n**Proposed
